WEBVTT

00:01.151 --> 00:02.150
<i> Previously on</i> The Resident...

00:02.253 --> 00:04.986
Nicolette Marie Nevin,

00:05.006 --> 00:06.505
will you do me the honor...

00:06.698 --> 00:08.415
<i> ANDREA:</i>
<i> He's one of a kind, isn't he?</i>

00:08.567 --> 00:09.399
Yeah.

00:09.460 --> 00:10.843
<i> Our relationship--</i>

00:11.036 --> 00:13.178
it is perfect just like this.

00:13.371 --> 00:14.346
My father owns his own cab.

00:14.539 --> 00:15.681
He put me through medical school

00:15.874 --> 00:16.923
working very long hours,

00:17.076 --> 00:18.350
and I'm very proud of him.

00:18.543 --> 00:20.244
So, y-you think this place
in Savannah--

00:20.304 --> 00:22.079
you really think
they can help me?

00:22.097 --> 00:23.914
It's one of the best inpatient
centers in the country.

00:23.974 --> 00:25.916
I really want to be there
for all those moments

00:25.976 --> 00:26.917
that you talked about.

00:26.935 --> 00:28.176
Me too.

00:28.237 --> 00:29.511
KIM:
Cain and Bell had their chance

00:29.530 --> 00:30.754
to be the star of this company,

00:30.814 --> 00:31.679
but they couldn't deliver.

00:31.699 --> 00:33.090
Our future is brighter

00:33.150 --> 00:35.451
with Conrad Hawkins
front and center.

00:43.085 --> 00:45.085
I don't know.

00:46.288 --> 00:47.938
I'm still jonesing
for that powder blue tux

00:47.998 --> 00:50.791
with the ruffled shirt.

00:50.926 --> 00:53.201
No, no, no, no, no,
you are not allowed to look

00:53.262 --> 00:55.629
like a lounge singer
on your wedding day.

00:55.723 --> 00:59.207
Seriously... thoughts?

00:59.268 --> 01:01.451
You fishing for compliments?

01:01.512 --> 01:03.620
-(chuckles)
-Come on.

01:03.680 --> 01:05.189
Okay.

01:10.929 --> 01:12.738
Baller.

01:12.931 --> 01:14.481
Slightly different guy
than that jerk you met

01:14.633 --> 01:16.724
your first day of residency.

01:16.786 --> 01:18.969
You were just doing your job
the wrong way.

01:19.029 --> 01:20.487
I must've done something right.

01:20.623 --> 01:22.998
You turned
into a damn fine doctor.

01:25.294 --> 01:31.173
Yeah, well, it...
hasn't always felt that way.

01:32.968 --> 01:34.259
When all hell breaks loose,

01:34.452 --> 01:36.169
you find out what people
are made of.

01:36.263 --> 01:37.638
You excelled.

01:39.600 --> 01:42.826
That's very kind of you,
but let's stick to you.

01:42.845 --> 01:43.994
How you feeling?

01:44.054 --> 01:46.921
Any last-minute jitters?

01:46.941 --> 01:49.108
None.

01:49.301 --> 01:52.185
I'm as happy as I've ever been.

01:52.279 --> 01:55.072
I'm about to marry my soul mate.

01:56.975 --> 01:59.526
Okay, last stitch.

02:00.812 --> 02:03.938
Something borrowed
and something blue.

02:03.999 --> 02:05.031
It's a twofer.

02:05.126 --> 02:06.850
Those earrings are beautiful.

02:06.910 --> 02:08.018
Whose are they?

02:08.120 --> 02:10.687
They were Jessie's.

02:10.789 --> 02:13.090
My dad bought them
for her 16th birthday.

02:15.160 --> 02:17.027
I wish she were here.

02:17.087 --> 02:18.953
(sighs)
Me, too.

02:19.014 --> 02:21.140
But she's always with me.

02:21.333 --> 02:23.976
-So is my mom.
-Hmm.

02:24.127 --> 02:28.372
And now you get to wear
her circa-1980

02:28.390 --> 02:30.374
-wedding dress.
-(chuckles)

02:30.434 --> 02:33.468
When my dad begged me
to wear it, my heart sank.

02:33.529 --> 02:36.229
(laughs)
Luckily you have Mina.

02:36.382 --> 02:37.322
Something old is now new.

02:37.515 --> 02:40.826
I mean, you're a miracle worker.

02:41.019 --> 02:41.976
-Thank you.
-Of course.

02:42.037 --> 02:44.054
(Nic sighs)

02:44.114 --> 02:46.890
Is it bad to be this happy after
everything that's happened?

02:46.950 --> 02:49.317
(sighs)
No,

02:49.420 --> 02:53.730
but I wish
things had been different,

02:53.790 --> 02:57.342
that we could all be here
together today.

02:57.535 --> 02:59.178
Yeah.

02:59.371 --> 03:04.999
(inhales)
2020, man, what a year.

03:05.019 --> 03:07.835
I mean, we had no idea
what was about to hit us.

03:07.897 --> 03:11.190
(sighs)

03:15.187 --> 03:17.345
Okay, since the service
is outside,

03:17.364 --> 03:19.180
I was thinking,
instead of throwing rice,

03:19.241 --> 03:20.532
people could throw birdseeds?

03:20.725 --> 03:23.443
Environmentally conscious--
I like it.

03:23.537 --> 03:25.186
(laughs)

03:25.206 --> 03:26.705
Okay, how do you feel
about a buffet

03:26.898 --> 03:28.615
instead of a seated dinner?

03:28.709 --> 03:30.617
I feel nothing.

03:30.711 --> 03:31.935
Defer.

03:31.995 --> 03:33.770
Band or DJ?

03:33.830 --> 03:34.938
Up to you.

03:34.998 --> 03:36.548
Oh, my God, we're bad at this.

03:36.741 --> 03:37.791
Okay, I'm going DJ.

03:37.927 --> 03:39.384
All right.

03:39.577 --> 03:41.220
And I think I want
burgundy flowers.

03:41.371 --> 03:44.389
Dahlias, peonies.

03:44.582 --> 03:48.118
Really? I was hoping
for blue wildflowers.

03:48.136 --> 03:49.803
You don't care
what music we play

03:49.955 --> 03:51.621
and yet you have an opinion
on the color of my bouquet?

03:51.682 --> 03:54.716
Remember that first date we had,
hiking at Sweetwater?

03:54.777 --> 03:57.644
The flowers I picked
for you that day?

03:57.738 --> 04:00.072
Blue wildflowers it is.

04:00.265 --> 04:01.631
And whatever DJ you decide on,

04:01.733 --> 04:04.134
they have to play
"Mr. Brightside."

04:04.194 --> 04:06.728
You asked.
(laughs)

04:06.747 --> 04:08.321
I thought you had
better taste than that.

04:08.457 --> 04:10.323
Oh, you're about to be
Mrs. Conrad Hawkins.

04:10.476 --> 04:11.992
We both should have
better taste.

04:12.144 --> 04:15.069
I'm pretty sure<i> you're</i>
about to be Mr. Nic Nevin.

04:15.130 --> 04:18.966
♪<i> No more, no work.</i> ♪

04:21.878 --> 04:23.578
Okafor.

04:23.597 --> 04:26.172
Quadruple bypass in an hour.
Get your game on.

04:26.308 --> 04:28.842
My game is always on.

04:28.936 --> 04:30.084
-(phone ringing)
-That's what I love about you.

04:30.145 --> 04:31.085
Andrea.

04:31.146 --> 04:33.346
<i> Mon chéri.</i>

04:33.440 --> 04:35.348
Yeah, I will be
picking you up at 8:00

04:35.501 --> 04:38.351
for Chateaubriand
at Chez Pierre.

04:38.445 --> 04:39.945
(laughs)

04:40.138 --> 04:42.839
Do not dis my French accent.

04:42.858 --> 04:44.283
I loathe the in-love Raptor.

04:44.476 --> 04:46.618
Maybe you should
ask yourself why.

04:46.811 --> 04:48.862
<i> MAN (over P.A.):</i>
<i> Transition team to OR Four.</i>

04:48.956 --> 04:51.272
<i> Transition team</i>
<i> to OR Four.</i>

04:51.292 --> 04:53.183
Look who it is.

04:53.243 --> 04:54.626
-The new face of the hospital.
-(chuckles)

04:54.819 --> 04:56.369
Not.

04:56.463 --> 04:58.463
Why is Barrett Cain's mug
still up there?

04:58.656 --> 05:00.190
CONRAD:
Randolph Bell, Barrett Cain,

05:00.250 --> 05:02.116
then Conrad Hawkins?

05:02.219 --> 05:03.951
Hard pass, thank you very much.

05:04.013 --> 05:05.453
(laughs)

05:05.556 --> 05:06.621
Hey, do you have time
for a quick consult?

05:06.682 --> 05:08.048
Sure.

05:08.200 --> 05:10.216
Bay One, Carter Wiggins, 34.

05:10.352 --> 05:13.053
Headache, febrile and fatigue.

05:13.188 --> 05:14.629
Take a look at his hands
over here.

05:14.690 --> 05:15.963
Hello, Mr. Wiggins.

05:15.983 --> 05:17.223
-I'm Dr. Hawkins.
-(coughing)

05:17.376 --> 05:18.483
Sounds like
you're feeling lousy.

05:18.635 --> 05:20.226
So these, um, red lesions
are new.

05:20.379 --> 05:22.654
And my nose is all stopped up.

05:22.823 --> 05:24.156
Can't smell my pies,

05:24.307 --> 05:26.232
even the pineapple
and pepperoni.

05:26.327 --> 05:28.142
HUNDLEY:
Can't believe
you went to work today.

05:28.162 --> 05:29.569
Your mama would be angry.

05:29.663 --> 05:31.788
-(coughing)
-Temp is up to 102.5.

05:33.042 --> 05:34.649
Have you traveled
anywhere recently?

05:34.752 --> 05:36.409
Uh, Seattle.

05:36.562 --> 05:39.004
To see my grandmother.

05:39.197 --> 05:40.672
Okay, we'll be right back.

05:47.798 --> 05:50.307
How many cases of COVID-19
in Seattle?

05:54.021 --> 05:55.687
14 known so far, five deaths.

05:55.856 --> 05:58.190
DEVON:
The symptoms fit.

05:58.359 --> 06:00.233
I think we have our first case
of coronavirus.

06:02.696 --> 06:05.088
-(alarm beeping)
-HUNDLEY: We need a crash cart!

06:05.107 --> 06:06.073
I've lost his pulse.

06:07.359 --> 06:10.160
Hundley, stop!
You need PPE.

06:15.584 --> 06:17.417
♪ ♪

06:31.892 --> 06:33.225
<i> (siren wailing)</i>

06:33.418 --> 06:35.352
(newswoman speaking
indistinctly)

06:48.784 --> 06:50.909
(phone chimes)

06:51.060 --> 06:52.577
NIC:
Just got a text.

06:52.770 --> 06:55.138
They can't refund the deposit
for the wedding venue.

06:55.157 --> 06:56.473
CONRAD:
Someday this will be over

06:56.533 --> 06:58.642
and we will have
a beautiful wedding.

06:58.660 --> 07:00.919
NIC: It seems petty
to even be talking about that.

07:01.088 --> 07:02.254
No, it's not petty.

07:03.757 --> 07:05.590
Just want everyone
to get to that day safely.

07:08.753 --> 07:11.721
-(beeps)
-(beeps)

07:22.401 --> 07:24.776
You guys,
I've got Hundley on speaker.

07:24.928 --> 07:26.352
<i> (Hundley coughing)</i>

07:26.488 --> 07:28.855
Hey, Hundley, it's Devon.
What's your O2 sat?

07:28.949 --> 07:30.857
<i> 90. But don't worry.</i>

07:31.009 --> 07:34.268
I just had... a coughing fit,

07:34.329 --> 07:36.179
so it'll come back up.

07:36.239 --> 07:38.623
(coughing)

07:40.118 --> 07:41.201
Mom, are you okay?

07:41.295 --> 07:43.444
Mom, I'm coming in.

07:43.464 --> 07:44.854
No, you're not, honey!

07:44.915 --> 07:46.356
(coughing)

07:46.374 --> 07:47.615
Mom!

07:47.634 --> 07:48.875
MINA:
Is there anything we can do?

07:48.969 --> 07:50.284
<i> (panting):</i>
<i> Don't,</i>

07:50.345 --> 07:52.378
<i> don't worry about me.</i>

07:52.473 --> 07:54.139
CONRAD: Not possible.
You should come in.

07:54.332 --> 07:56.716
I'll know if the time comes

07:56.810 --> 07:58.292
when I need you.

07:58.353 --> 08:00.353
<i> (coughing, wheezing)</i>

08:03.192 --> 08:04.874
Mom, I'm getting scared.

08:04.935 --> 08:05.817
Please come unlock the door.

08:06.010 --> 08:07.544
(rattling)

08:07.604 --> 08:09.637
(hacking)

08:09.698 --> 08:10.989
Don't come in.

08:11.158 --> 08:12.232
Okay, I'm-I'm
officially worried.

08:12.384 --> 08:13.492
Seriously.

08:13.660 --> 08:15.068
This is day five
of the same mask.

08:15.162 --> 08:16.310
Can you check my seal?

08:16.371 --> 08:17.287
Yep.

08:20.501 --> 08:21.458
Seal's holding.

08:23.003 --> 08:25.912
♪ ♪

08:26.006 --> 08:28.565
You ready?

08:28.625 --> 08:29.633
Let's go.

08:32.846 --> 08:34.754
I don't think I ever realized
how many of our surgeries

08:34.890 --> 08:36.406
are actually elective.

08:36.424 --> 08:37.999
AUSTIN: I have patients
who need operations

08:38.060 --> 08:39.242
who won't come in.

08:39.302 --> 08:40.760
They're worried it's not safe.

08:40.912 --> 08:42.670
BELL:
You know, I've never felt

08:42.731 --> 08:43.763
quite so useless.

08:43.857 --> 08:45.190
NOLAN:
So what do we do?

08:45.341 --> 08:47.433
Well, I'd say
we join the front lines.

08:47.528 --> 08:49.361
Mina's been in the ER all week.

08:49.512 --> 08:51.178
-Same as Kit, in the ICU.
-Well, that's all well and good,

08:51.240 --> 08:52.697
except I got this
preexisting condition...

08:52.890 --> 08:55.275
-Cowardice?
-(Austin laughs)

08:55.369 --> 08:57.277
Time to put on
the big boy pants, Nolan.

08:57.371 --> 08:59.454
We got work to do, baby.

09:03.043 --> 09:04.117
<i> C-Can he hear us?</i>

09:04.253 --> 09:06.027
KIT:
I believe so.

09:06.088 --> 09:08.029
Say whatever
you have to say now;

09:08.090 --> 09:09.548
it won't be much longer.

09:09.699 --> 09:12.008
<i> We will be here</i>
<i> long as it takes.</i>

09:14.221 --> 09:16.054
<i> He can't die alone.</i>

09:17.099 --> 09:19.140
I'll give you some privacy.

09:24.922 --> 09:27.607
♪ ♪

09:49.614 --> 09:51.423
♪ ♪

10:00.124 --> 10:02.008
(alarm beeping)

10:02.144 --> 10:04.185
(indistinct chatter)

10:06.607 --> 10:09.316
♪ ♪

10:31.581 --> 10:33.857
♪ ♪

10:33.917 --> 10:36.283
(monitor beeping)

10:36.303 --> 10:37.451
-(pounding on door)
-PUND (muffled): Dr. Bell!

10:37.471 --> 10:38.452
Dr. Bell.

10:38.555 --> 10:39.954
His sat is stuck in the 70s.

10:40.015 --> 10:41.598
What do you need?

11:02.821 --> 11:04.721
BELL:
Hey.

11:04.823 --> 11:06.222
What's going on?

11:06.282 --> 11:08.224
KIT:
(sighs) Everything.

11:08.243 --> 11:09.483
I feel so helpless.

11:09.544 --> 11:12.504
We're surgeons. We cut, we fix.

11:12.655 --> 11:14.822
With this disease,
there's so little we can do.

11:14.883 --> 11:17.825
Just hold their hands
and support them.

11:17.928 --> 11:20.570
And too many are dying
in these rooms, alone.

11:20.588 --> 11:23.330
BELL:
You should go home.
You're exhausted.

11:23.392 --> 11:25.049
KIT:
You should.

11:25.185 --> 11:26.834
It's too dangerous for you here.

11:26.895 --> 11:29.521
People over 65 are most at risk.

11:29.690 --> 11:31.581
BELL:
I'm 60.

11:31.641 --> 11:34.083
Roughly.

11:34.185 --> 11:36.385
I'm fit. I run marathons.

11:36.479 --> 11:38.087
KIT:
That's Pete.

11:38.189 --> 11:40.106
He's a tennis pro,

11:40.200 --> 11:43.368
now with myocarditis
as a result of this virus.

11:43.561 --> 11:45.203
He's 33 and he might die.

11:45.396 --> 11:47.372
Fit won't save you.

11:47.565 --> 11:49.249
BELL:
Well, I'm staying.

11:50.752 --> 11:52.285
(phone chimes)

11:52.421 --> 11:53.878
MINA:
Hundley just pulled in.

11:54.030 --> 11:56.256
She's not doing well.
She drove herself.

11:59.219 --> 12:01.202
(panting)

12:01.221 --> 12:04.055
(siren wailing)

12:08.419 --> 12:10.437
(grunts)

12:16.945 --> 12:17.902
DEVON:
Hundley!

12:18.054 --> 12:19.279
Hundley, hang on!

12:32.143 --> 12:35.128
-MINA: We've got Hundley!
-IRVING: Put her in Bay Three.

12:35.279 --> 12:37.422
MINA:
Sat 78, pulse 150 and climbing.

12:37.615 --> 12:39.148
NIC:
I'll start an IV.

12:39.250 --> 12:40.650
CONRAD:
Mina, she needs oxygen.

12:40.668 --> 12:42.318
MINA: Get her started
on a non-rebreather.

12:42.420 --> 12:45.054
-(Hundley coughing)
-DEVON: And 500cc's of saline.

12:54.191 --> 12:55.999
(panting)

12:56.017 --> 12:56.882
You got this.

12:56.985 --> 12:58.610
We got this.

13:01.782 --> 13:02.989
NIC:
Here you go.

13:04.267 --> 13:06.117
All right?

13:06.310 --> 13:07.527
Temp is 102.6.

13:07.621 --> 13:10.121
DEVON:
Okay, her sats are rising. 92.

13:10.290 --> 13:12.515
-94.
-HUNDLEY: Oxygen's helping.

13:12.534 --> 13:14.684
Don't intubate
if you can avoid it.

13:14.786 --> 13:17.203
I need to stay awake
for Raylee. Promise.

13:17.355 --> 13:19.113
NIC:
We're gonna do everything
we can to take care of you.

13:19.174 --> 13:21.190
RAYLEE:
Mom!

13:21.251 --> 13:22.449
HUNDLEY:
Oh, oh, my baby.

13:22.511 --> 13:24.043
Send her home where she's safe.

13:24.137 --> 13:26.304
-Get her out of here.
-I will. I promise.

13:26.497 --> 13:29.048
DEVON:
Hundley, we need to admit you,

13:29.200 --> 13:30.716
get you to the ICU, okay?

13:30.852 --> 13:32.385
IRVING:
I'm putting in the orders now.

13:32.521 --> 13:33.961
MINA:
Checking for available beds.

13:34.022 --> 13:35.296
Hang in there.

13:36.891 --> 13:38.632
RAYLEE:
Nic, please. She wouldn't
even let me drive her here.

13:38.693 --> 13:40.634
I have to see her.

13:40.728 --> 13:42.303
NIC:
Raylee, we can't have visitors

13:42.364 --> 13:43.637
-in the hospital right now.
-RAYLEE: Please.

13:43.698 --> 13:44.897
You know my mom.

13:44.991 --> 13:46.382
She's there for me
when I'm sick.

13:46.401 --> 13:47.884
I can't just leave.

13:47.944 --> 13:49.810
Listen, first off all,
are you feeling okay?

13:49.830 --> 13:52.722
Good. So, your mom wants you
to go home and isolate.

13:52.824 --> 13:54.223
Take care of yourself,
and I will call you

13:54.325 --> 13:55.725
as soon as she's settled, okay?

13:55.785 --> 13:57.961
I'm so sorry.

14:03.626 --> 14:05.326
<i> KIM:</i>
<i> We're bleeding money.</i>

14:05.387 --> 14:07.904
Down $400 million
in a single month.

14:07.964 --> 14:10.423
Uh, you hold the fate
of the hospital in your hands.

14:10.517 --> 14:12.666
Red Rock needs you
to start cutting again.

14:12.727 --> 14:14.835
CAIN:
Can't cut. Everyone's afraid.

14:14.896 --> 14:16.003
Especially the sickest people

14:16.022 --> 14:17.355
who need the operations
the most.

14:17.524 --> 14:19.023
They're afraid COVID
is gonna kill them.

14:19.175 --> 14:20.841
KIM:
Then-then focus
on elective surgeries.

14:20.902 --> 14:24.011
Stents, uh, knee replacements,
disc repair, uh, plastics.

14:24.030 --> 14:25.530
BELL:
It's against CMS guidelines.

14:25.699 --> 14:27.198
KIT:
Elective surgeries
use precious PPE,

14:27.391 --> 14:29.534
hospital beds and resources.

14:29.727 --> 14:31.444
KIM:
We don't have
a multibillion-dollar endowment

14:31.538 --> 14:33.613
like the Mayo Clinic.
I have to make payroll.

14:33.707 --> 14:36.449
D-Do you understand
that this hospital will close?

14:36.543 --> 14:38.859
-Thousands of jobs are at stake.
-AUSTIN: Yeah, but the only job

14:38.879 --> 14:40.603
you're worried about
is your own, Kim.

14:40.663 --> 14:42.605
-KIM: That's not true.
-Really?

14:42.624 --> 14:44.698
KIM:
I-I know we haven't always
been on the same side,

14:44.759 --> 14:46.718
but we need to work together
this time.

14:46.869 --> 14:48.611
BELL:
There's a government bailout
coming.

14:48.671 --> 14:51.297
-Where will that money go?
-KIT: Red Rock's bank account.

14:51.449 --> 14:53.600
-(Bell laughs)
-AUSTIN: Yeah. We're done here.

14:56.271 --> 14:57.186
KIM:
B-Barrett.

14:58.607 --> 15:01.140
You're the chief of surgery.
My rainmaker.

15:01.234 --> 15:04.644
I... Help me to save Chastain.

15:04.738 --> 15:05.978
Take the lowest-risk
elective surgeries

15:06.072 --> 15:08.389
and-and schedule them as urgent.

15:08.450 --> 15:11.926
CAIN:
Okay, on one condition.

15:11.928 --> 15:14.820
Don't ever threaten my job again
or replace my face

15:14.956 --> 15:18.583
on the side of this building
with a shiny new object.

15:18.776 --> 15:20.418
KIM:
Deal.

15:31.747 --> 15:33.681
(line ringing)

15:35.259 --> 15:37.418
(phone ringing)

15:37.479 --> 15:39.920
(sighs)

15:39.940 --> 15:41.773
Dr. Cain?

15:41.966 --> 15:43.666
<i> Is there something wrong?</i>

15:43.726 --> 15:45.184
I'm afraid so.

15:45.336 --> 15:46.444
Listen, I know that I told you

15:46.637 --> 15:48.446
your back surgery
could wait, Ben,

15:48.597 --> 15:52.116
but I took another look
at your last scan this morning.

15:53.119 --> 15:54.285
Is there a problem?

15:54.478 --> 15:55.845
<i> Yes. I see some progression</i>

15:55.905 --> 15:59.457
in your disc herniation
at your L5-S1 vertebrae

15:59.650 --> 16:01.960
with some potential involvement
of your spinal cord.

16:02.153 --> 16:05.371
-My spinal cord?
<i> -Yes, yes,</i>
<i> and it's getting worse.</i>

16:05.465 --> 16:08.024
I need to get you
into the OR immediately.

16:08.042 --> 16:10.468
But it's not safe
at the hospital.

16:10.661 --> 16:13.471
-The coronavirus is...
<i> -Oh, no, our surgical</i>
<i> facilities are pristine.</i>

16:13.664 --> 16:15.622
Yeah, never been cleaner
or safer.

16:15.725 --> 16:17.383
And you won't be anywhere near
a COVID patient.

16:17.477 --> 16:19.051
<i> We'll take every precaution.</i>

16:19.145 --> 16:21.628
(exhales)

16:21.648 --> 16:25.374
I don't know.
Um, I have to think about this.

16:25.393 --> 16:28.653
See, here's the thing, Ben,

16:28.846 --> 16:31.823
if you put this off,
you take one bad step,

16:32.016 --> 16:33.992
<i> you slip and fall</i>
<i> in the bathroom...</i>

16:35.036 --> 16:36.852
...you'll end up paralyzed.

16:36.871 --> 16:39.497
Oh, my God, Dr. Cain.

16:39.690 --> 16:41.457
(exhales)

16:43.420 --> 16:46.004
Okay.

16:46.197 --> 16:47.630
I'll do whatever you say.

16:56.040 --> 16:57.640
(phone ringing)

16:59.043 --> 17:00.243
Devon?

17:00.303 --> 17:02.353
How are you?

17:03.523 --> 17:05.523
Are you driving your cab again?

17:05.716 --> 17:06.691
That's one of the riskiest
things you could do.

17:06.842 --> 17:08.584
You promised me you'd stay home.

17:08.686 --> 17:11.087
-And who is going
to pay my rent, Devon?
<i> -I will.</i>

17:11.105 --> 17:14.090
<i> Listen, Dad, our ER is packed.</i>
<i> Our ICU, too.</i>

17:14.108 --> 17:16.200
Think about Mom.
You could get infected,

17:16.393 --> 17:17.535
<i> you could take it home to her,</i>
<i> she could die.</i>

17:17.728 --> 17:19.278
<i> You both could.</i>

17:19.430 --> 17:22.448
I need you to turn that cab
around and go home now.

17:22.600 --> 17:24.617
Dad, you need to leave
the facility and quarantine now.

17:24.753 --> 17:27.119
It's really not a good time,
Nicky. I'm only--

17:27.272 --> 17:28.862
-I'm halfway through treatment.
If I leave...
<i> -I know,</i>

17:28.923 --> 17:31.123
<i> but I wouldn't be asking</i>
<i> if it wasn't serious.</i>

17:31.276 --> 17:33.033
Please. I'll get you
a hotel room.

17:33.094 --> 17:34.385
Just tell me you'll do this.

17:37.173 --> 17:40.058
Yeah, okay. Okay, okay. Uh...

17:40.251 --> 17:42.376
Anything for you, Nicky.

17:42.437 --> 17:44.228
Okay.

17:45.106 --> 17:47.732
Dad, where are you?

17:47.883 --> 17:50.068
I finally got a guy
who's willing to manufacture

17:50.261 --> 17:52.311
the new mask prototypes,

17:52.463 --> 17:55.981
<i> but now he is telling me that</i>
<i> there are no more materials.</i>

17:56.134 --> 17:59.560
You have Crohn's disease
and a compromised immune system.

17:59.579 --> 18:01.562
We agreed that you were
gonna work from home.

18:01.623 --> 18:03.915
Hear my voice.
This is me not happy with you.

18:04.066 --> 18:05.750
<i> You need to solve</i>
<i> this issue from home.</i>

18:05.943 --> 18:07.476
As soon as I'm finished here.

18:07.495 --> 18:09.504
-(phone beeps)
-Hello?

18:14.252 --> 18:17.512
<i> This is Marshall Winthrop.</i>
<i> Unfort...</i>

18:21.959 --> 18:23.851
(siren wailing)

18:25.513 --> 18:28.922
CHAD:
Hey, you, nurse.
I've been waiting for two hours.

18:29.025 --> 18:31.183
I got gold-plated insurance.

18:31.336 --> 18:32.668
-The taxes I pay,
I should be first in line.
-MINA: Hey, hey, hey.

18:32.687 --> 18:34.612
There's no special treatment
in this ER.

18:34.763 --> 18:36.522
Put your mask up, six feet apart
or you're out of here.

18:36.658 --> 18:38.950
I am six feet apart.

18:39.101 --> 18:41.101
What are you trying to do,
set a world record for people

18:41.162 --> 18:43.162
in an ER in the middle
of a pandemic?

18:44.457 --> 18:46.532
MINA:
I understand the male temptation

18:46.626 --> 18:48.084
to exaggerate length...

18:49.129 --> 18:51.354
...but you need to back up.

18:51.455 --> 18:53.022
(gasps)

18:53.082 --> 18:54.966
What-- Don't touch me!

18:55.159 --> 18:57.218
He's not six feet apart!

19:01.558 --> 19:04.367
IRVING:
We've got five minutes
before our next crisis.

19:04.427 --> 19:06.369
-JESSICA: It is crazy out there.
-IRVING: And unsafe.

19:06.387 --> 19:07.887
I really wish
you were back in the OR

19:08.022 --> 19:09.388
working as a scrub nurse.

19:09.482 --> 19:11.315
JESSICA:
I'm right where I want to be.

19:18.199 --> 19:20.283
I'm laying my head
on your shoulder right now.

19:23.221 --> 19:27.223
IRVING:
I'm holding you
and rocking you back and forth.

19:27.241 --> 19:29.208
JESSICA:
Aw. Thank you.

19:46.543 --> 19:48.853
"Lower extremity weakness
and acute onset

19:49.046 --> 19:54.007
of bowel incontinence requiring
urgent operative management."

19:54.068 --> 19:58.154
Come on, he's a 58-year-old
with a simple bulging disc.

20:03.060 --> 20:05.703
We are in the midst
of the single most devastating

20:05.896 --> 20:08.372
public health crisis
of our lifetimes.

20:09.191 --> 20:10.041
Barrett, you can't be
doing surgeries

20:10.192 --> 20:11.542
that don't need to be done.

20:11.711 --> 20:14.045
You put a patient at risk
of getting COVID.

20:14.238 --> 20:17.030
20% of surgeries
are unnecessary.

20:17.091 --> 20:18.624
I made a judgment call.

20:18.718 --> 20:23.012
And he won't get COVID
because my OR is spotless.

20:26.842 --> 20:30.377
You know, you had a chance
to do the right thing.

20:30.438 --> 20:33.547
Pitch in with the rest of us
and help, but no.

20:33.608 --> 20:36.976
You just followed
Red Rock's marching orders.

20:37.128 --> 20:38.627
I'm a neurosurgeon. I cut.

20:38.646 --> 20:41.888
When that pandemic
can be cured by brain surgery,

20:41.950 --> 20:44.283
shoot me a page.

20:50.083 --> 20:52.065
HUNDLEY:
It's okay, Raylee.

20:52.126 --> 20:57.237
If you get a fever or cough,
don't panic.

20:57.257 --> 21:01.817
Most people don't get this sick.

21:01.919 --> 21:03.986
You're gonna be okay.

21:04.088 --> 21:06.764
My doctors are here.

21:06.957 --> 21:08.491
I'll call you back soon.

21:08.592 --> 21:10.417
-I love you.
<i> -RAYLEE: I love you, Mom.</i>

21:10.520 --> 21:12.177
-(phone beeps)
-BELL: Hey, there.

21:12.272 --> 21:14.254
(Hundley panting)

21:14.357 --> 21:17.775
Proning isn't working, is it?

21:17.926 --> 21:20.427
BELL:
Well, your O2 sats
are still dipping too low,

21:20.488 --> 21:22.521
so we're gonna try
a high-flow nasal cannula now.

21:22.673 --> 21:24.264
CONRAD:
It is a little outside the box,

21:24.325 --> 21:28.101
but otherwise
we have to intubate.

21:28.162 --> 21:32.790
If you put me to sleep
and put that tube in,

21:32.983 --> 21:36.335
there's a good chance
I won't wake up again.

21:39.457 --> 21:42.049
Which is why high-flow
is worth the risk.

21:52.145 --> 21:54.127
Okay.

21:54.188 --> 21:56.722
On three. One, two, three.

21:56.858 --> 21:59.692
(groaning, panting)

22:06.901 --> 22:11.645
-KIT: Uh-oh, we disconnected
something.
-(alarm beeping)

22:11.664 --> 22:13.497
-BELL: Where do these go?
-Haven't a clue.

22:13.690 --> 22:15.816
White electrode...

22:15.877 --> 22:19.228
under right clavicle.

22:19.246 --> 22:21.488
Black under left.
(groans)

22:21.549 --> 22:25.751
Red above and left of umbilicus.

22:25.845 --> 22:27.586
What about the beeping?

22:27.680 --> 22:29.013
Just press "silence."

22:31.684 --> 22:33.184
(beeping stops)

22:34.878 --> 22:37.262
Surgeons, huh?

22:37.357 --> 22:39.081
Nurses aren't paid enough.

22:39.183 --> 22:41.567
Tell me about it.
(coughing)

22:44.647 --> 22:45.921
(panting)

22:45.981 --> 22:48.324
You're gonna be okay.

22:52.955 --> 22:54.205
(coughs)

23:22.059 --> 23:23.292
Snapped when I was in the room.

23:23.352 --> 23:25.152
I thought I felt something.

23:28.557 --> 23:30.241
<i> CONRAD:</i>
<i> Europe, South Korea, China,</i>

23:30.434 --> 23:32.076
they all have state-of-the-art
protection; look at this.

23:32.269 --> 23:34.561
Dr. Voss is a surgeon.
Could have gone home

23:34.622 --> 23:36.305
'cause she doesn't have
any patients, but she's working

23:36.323 --> 23:37.748
in the ICU, and this is all
that protected her

23:37.900 --> 23:40.476
from exposure to COVID-19.
She's been exposed.

23:40.578 --> 23:42.978
You are sending our soldiers
to face the enemy

23:43.038 --> 23:45.238
without any armor.

23:45.258 --> 23:46.740
We have a top ER nurse
in the ICU

23:46.801 --> 23:48.500
fighting for her life.

23:48.594 --> 23:52.321
Two transpo workers are dead.
Med students, residents,

23:52.423 --> 23:54.156
they're isolating
from their families,

23:54.175 --> 23:55.507
they're sick and alone,
and some of them may die.

23:55.660 --> 23:57.101
Everybody is chasing
the same shipments.

23:57.252 --> 23:58.677
I keep getting outbid
by other hospitals.

23:58.829 --> 24:00.829
You need to protect our staff.
That's your job.

24:00.890 --> 24:02.923
I feel your frustration.
I-I do.

24:02.984 --> 24:05.017
My frustration? Why-why don't
you come down to my ER

24:05.153 --> 24:07.111
and share my frustration
instead of sitting

24:07.304 --> 24:09.429
in your ivory tower
doing nothing?!

24:09.490 --> 24:13.008
All of you think I don't care.
I care.

24:13.068 --> 24:15.602
I can't escape this either.

24:15.663 --> 24:17.863
This morning, a woman,
a total stranger,

24:18.015 --> 24:19.515
called me a bat eater.

24:19.575 --> 24:22.293
I'm sorry. That's terrible.

24:22.444 --> 24:24.687
The "China Virus,"
the "Kung Flu."

24:24.788 --> 24:26.797
I was born in Savannah.

24:26.949 --> 24:29.449
This is being used to turn us
all against each other.

24:29.510 --> 24:31.952
And yes, I am trying
to save this hospital.

24:32.013 --> 24:33.362
I'll-I'll bend the rules
to do it,

24:33.422 --> 24:34.955
but do not think for one moment

24:35.057 --> 24:37.582
that this hasn't hit me hard.

24:37.685 --> 24:39.477
I am human.

24:39.670 --> 24:42.021
Prove it.

24:45.526 --> 24:47.318
Prove it.

24:52.182 --> 24:55.234
(distant siren wailing)

24:55.328 --> 24:58.454
Yo. How you holding up?

25:00.666 --> 25:04.150
I don't know.
It's pretty rough in there.

25:04.212 --> 25:06.912
I'm proud of you for
working the ER;

25:07.064 --> 25:09.414
however, I need you in the OR.

25:09.509 --> 25:11.383
We have our first COVID trach.

25:13.796 --> 25:16.238
Sounds delightful.

25:16.298 --> 25:17.923
(both laugh)

25:18.059 --> 25:21.001
Well, seriously,
you could use the break.

25:21.062 --> 25:22.761
I'm worried about you.

25:22.855 --> 25:26.524
I'm worried about you, too.

25:30.887 --> 25:32.363
Okay.

25:32.514 --> 25:35.591
You know where to find me
if you need me.

25:35.609 --> 25:37.117
I certainly do.

25:43.400 --> 25:47.786
CONRAD:
The high-flow bought us time,
but...

25:47.938 --> 25:51.590
your sat is 82% on 100% oxygen,

25:51.717 --> 25:54.109
and it is dropping.

25:54.169 --> 25:56.554
We need to intubate.

25:56.722 --> 25:59.306
(stifled sobbing)

26:03.729 --> 26:07.122
-Can you get Chu?
-He's on his way.

26:07.224 --> 26:09.382
(Hundley crying)

26:09.443 --> 26:12.552
Can you please tell Raylee
I love her again?

26:12.572 --> 26:16.407
You will tell her yourself
because you will wake up.

26:16.558 --> 26:19.201
Now let us fight for you.

26:27.778 --> 26:30.963
-I'm here, Hundley. I'm here.
-(coughing)

26:32.800 --> 26:33.832
You're gonna be okay.

26:33.926 --> 26:37.136
-(sniffling)
-We're here.

26:39.923 --> 26:42.224
(sobbing softly)

26:48.316 --> 26:49.848
We're gonna put you to sleep
now, my friend.

26:49.942 --> 26:54.695
Just relax.
Just relax.

27:23.333 --> 27:27.019
-You haven't eaten all day.
-I can't eat.

27:30.191 --> 27:32.557
Hundley's a single mom.

27:32.693 --> 27:34.300
I don't want to have to
tell Raylee that

27:34.320 --> 27:35.986
she's never gonna see
her mom again.

27:39.216 --> 27:41.400
She's around the same age you
were when you lost your mom,

27:41.494 --> 27:43.285
isn't she?

27:50.652 --> 27:52.586
If you get COVID, I get COVID.

28:03.540 --> 28:05.849
The good news is
I can smell that coffee.

28:06.042 --> 28:07.743
And I could taste that bread.

28:07.761 --> 28:10.003
If it's my last meal,
I'm going out with carbs.

28:10.064 --> 28:12.231
Don't even say that.

28:14.919 --> 28:16.919
How's Kit?

28:16.979 --> 28:18.862
Her mask broke.

28:19.014 --> 28:21.448
She's been exposed.

28:23.351 --> 28:25.518
-(sighs)
-I told her to go home.

28:25.621 --> 28:28.122
She's scared.

28:34.755 --> 28:37.197
(Mina chuckles)

28:37.258 --> 28:40.776
You'd rather wear a PAPR
than shave your beard.

28:40.836 --> 28:44.370
(chuckles) You know how long
it takes to grow this beard out?

28:44.390 --> 28:46.056
You know we have
a limited number of these?

28:46.208 --> 28:47.616
They're for people who can't
wear N95s because of the way

28:47.634 --> 28:49.634
their faces are shaped,
or because they have

28:49.729 --> 28:51.453
a religious objection
to shaving their beards.

28:51.555 --> 28:54.139
Yeah, well, let's just say
I do have a religious objection.

28:54.233 --> 28:56.458
I worship this beard, all right?

28:56.477 --> 28:58.885
Well, you certainly are
conceited as you are vain.

28:58.988 --> 29:00.220
Isn't it itchy?

29:00.281 --> 29:02.573
Not at all.

29:04.744 --> 29:06.985
-All right, let me help you.
-Aw, thanks.

29:07.079 --> 29:08.728
Without the beard,
I look too young.

29:08.789 --> 29:10.730
It adds wisdom and gravitas,

29:10.791 --> 29:12.624
-and it's reassuring
to my patients.
-Mm.

29:18.466 --> 29:21.091
(laughs) Well, you don't
look reassuring to me.

29:21.243 --> 29:23.335
-You look like you're
about to go into space.
-Ha-ha-ha-ha.

29:23.429 --> 29:25.471
(device beeps, whirs)

29:28.258 --> 29:30.100
(air hissing)

29:32.254 --> 29:33.437
It's working.

29:35.274 --> 29:38.650
Yeah, it is.

29:56.912 --> 29:58.854
Where did you get it?

29:58.914 --> 30:00.522
South Korea.

30:00.624 --> 30:02.633
My family still has
relatives there.

30:02.826 --> 30:04.784
I put in an emergency order,

30:04.845 --> 30:07.787
and it turns out this shipment
was on its way.

30:07.848 --> 30:10.957
-It wasn't cheap getting it
diverted to Chastain.
-Wait, wait, wait.

30:11.060 --> 30:14.061
-You said Red Rock wouldn't pay.
-They won't.

30:15.147 --> 30:17.356
But they did.

30:20.677 --> 30:22.377
(sighs)

30:22.437 --> 30:24.304
What happens when they find out?

30:24.365 --> 30:27.049
Could cost me my job.

30:27.067 --> 30:30.569
But for now, at least our staff
will be protected.

30:30.721 --> 30:33.747
And I could sleep
a little better tonight.

30:59.859 --> 31:02.609
♪ ♪

31:05.030 --> 31:06.012
You never looked better.

31:06.073 --> 31:08.699
You, too.

31:08.892 --> 31:10.108
(both laugh)

31:10.202 --> 31:11.535
NIC:
Ready for the next shift?

31:11.686 --> 31:14.020
CONRAD:
Yeah. I'm ready.
And we are not

31:14.081 --> 31:16.582
leaving Hundley.

31:22.756 --> 31:25.790
♪<i> Whisper in my ear</i>
<i> it's time to go</i> ♪

31:25.926 --> 31:28.701
(indistinct radio chatter)

31:28.762 --> 31:32.130
♪<i> Head between your hands</i>
<i> but I feel cold...</i> ♪

31:32.224 --> 31:34.616
(cheering)

31:34.676 --> 31:39.146
♪<i> It's too hard to hold you up</i>
<i> and breathe</i> ♪

31:41.233 --> 31:46.128
♪<i> My heart is breaking up</i>
<i> the things it wants, yeah</i> ♪

31:46.188 --> 31:50.482
♪<i> My love, it ain't big enough</i> ♪

31:50.576 --> 31:54.152
♪<i> What if I can't reach</i> ♪

31:54.246 --> 31:56.729
♪<i> And pick you up next time?</i> ♪

31:56.749 --> 32:00.008
♪<i> What if I can't reach</i> ♪

32:00.010 --> 32:02.994
♪<i> And make you feel all right?</i> ♪

32:03.088 --> 32:05.589
♪<i> What if I can't reach</i> ♪

32:05.782 --> 32:08.483
♪<i> And pick you up next time?</i> ♪

32:08.502 --> 32:11.744
♪<i> What if I can't reach</i> ♪

32:11.805 --> 32:15.599
♪<i> And make you</i>
<i> feel all right...</i> ♪

32:15.792 --> 32:18.176
(line ringing)

32:18.270 --> 32:20.829
Hey, Dad, it's me.
Just calling to check in

32:20.847 --> 32:22.255
and make sure you're not driving

32:22.358 --> 32:26.017
<i> -your cab anymore.</i>
-(coughing)

32:26.111 --> 32:27.593
One second, son.

32:27.655 --> 32:30.280
<i> -(coughing)</i>
-Dad, what's going on?

32:30.473 --> 32:32.115
Nothing.

32:32.308 --> 32:34.451
I think I have a little flu,
that's all.

32:34.620 --> 32:37.770
♪<i> What if I can't reach</i> ♪

32:37.790 --> 32:40.457
♪<i> And pick you up next time?</i> ♪

32:40.650 --> 32:43.460
♪<i> What if I can't reach</i> ♪

32:43.653 --> 32:45.796
♪<i> And make you feel all right?</i> ♪

32:45.947 --> 32:50.875
♪<i> What if I can't reach, oh</i> ♪

32:50.970 --> 32:52.377
♪<i> Reach</i> ♪

32:52.471 --> 32:54.454
♪<i> What if I can't reach?</i> ♪

32:54.515 --> 32:56.139
♪<i> What if I can't</i> ♪

32:56.332 --> 32:58.200
♪<i> Reach?</i> ♪

32:58.260 --> 33:01.203
♪<i> What if I can't reach</i> ♪

33:01.263 --> 33:03.146
♪<i> And make you feel all right?</i> ♪

33:03.298 --> 33:04.389
(thermometer beeps)

33:04.525 --> 33:07.150
♪<i> What if I can't reach</i> ♪

33:07.343 --> 33:09.377
♪<i> And pick you up next time?</i> ♪

33:09.479 --> 33:12.547
♪<i> What if I can't reach</i> ♪

33:12.607 --> 33:15.325
♪<i> And make you feel all right?</i> ♪

33:15.518 --> 33:16.809
♪<i> What if I can't reach?</i> ♪

33:16.870 --> 33:19.145
Randolph...

33:19.164 --> 33:21.056
<i> I'm gonna need you to cover</i>
<i> my patients tomorrow.</i>

33:21.158 --> 33:23.000
(exhales)

33:23.193 --> 33:25.002
I have a fever.

